04531nam a22005175i 9780801459993DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20112011nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808014599937 a10.7591/97808014599932doi  a(DE-B1597)478589  a(OCoLC)979622586  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aPHI0160002bisacsh04a1932221 aIngram, David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHabermas :bIntroduction and Analysis /cDavid Ingram. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (384 p.) :b8 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Tables -- tPreface -- tAbbreviations for Titles of Works by Habermas -- t1. A Public Intellectual Committed to Reason -- t2. Habermas’s Defense of Psychoanalytic Social Science -- t3. The Linguistic Turn -- t4. Knowledge and Truth Revisited -- t5. Discourse Ethics -- t6. Law and Democracy: Part I: The Foundational Rights -- t7. Law and Democracy: Part II: Power and the Clash of Paradigms -- t8. Law and Democracy: Part III: Applying the Proceduralist Paradigm -- t9. Law and Democracy: Part IV: Social Complexity and a Critical Assessment -- t10. Crisis and Pathology: The Future of Democracy in a Global Age -- t11. Postsecular Postscript: Modernity and Its Discontents -- tAppendix A: Explaining Action -- tAppendix B: Understanding Action -- tAppendix C: Habermas and Brandom -- tAppendix D: Developmental Psychology -- tAppendix E: Rational Choice Theory -- tAppendix F: Systems Theory -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe work of Jürgen Habermas (b. 1929) has been highly influential both in philosophy and across many disciplines in the social sciences. David Ingram here provides an introduction to Habermas's complex thought as it has evolved from 1953 to the present, spanning philosophy, religion, political science, social science, and law. One of today's most intriguing thinkers, Habermas is also notably prolific; for students and other readers who wish to navigate the philosopher's more than thirty books, the lucid and precise Habermas: Introduction and Analysis is a welcome starting point rich in insights.Ingram's book addresses the entire range of Habermas's social theory, including his most recent and widely discussed contributions to religion, freedom and determinism, global democracy, and the consolidation of the European Union. Recognizing Habermas's position as a highly public intellectual, Ingram discusses how Habermas applies his own theory to pressing problems such as abortion, terrorism, genetic engineering, immigration, multiculturalism, separation of religion and state, technology and mass media, feminism, and human rights. He also presents a detailed critical analysis of Habermas's key claims and arguments.Separate appendixes introduce and clarify such important concepts as causal, teleological, and narrative paradigms of explanation in action theory; contextualism versus rationalism in social scientific methods of interpretation; systems theory and functionalist explanation in social science; and decision and collective choice theory.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aSocial sciencesxPhilosophy. 4aHistory. 4aPhilosophy. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Modern.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080145999340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801459993423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801459993/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d